  "prompt": "I have an aversion to shaking hands with strangers. How can I avoid this and not be rude?",
  "response": "It's completely understandable to feel uncomfortable with shaking hands, especially with strangers. Here are some suggestions for navigating this situation without coming across as rude:\n\n1. **Use Non-Verbal Cues**: Smile and nod as a greeting instead of extending your hand. This approach conveys friendliness without requiring physical contact.\n\n2. **Offer a Different Gesture**: You can use a wave, a fist bump, or even a slight bow as an alternative to a handshake. These gestures can be seen as respectful and friendly.\n\n3. **Be Honest**: If the context allows, you can simply explain your aversion to shaking hands in a light and friendly way, such as, \"I\u2019ve decided to avoid handshakes for personal reasons, but it's great to meet you!\"\n\n4. **Focus on Your Body Language**: Make eye contact and maintain an open posture to show that you are engaged and friendly. This helps put others at ease even without physical contact.\n\n5. **Redirect the Interaction**: If someone goes for a handshake, you can politely say, \u201cLet\u2019s skip the handshake. It\u2019s nice to meet you!\u201d and then proceed with conversation.\n\n6. **Carry Hand Sanitizer**: If you're concerned about germs, having hand sanitizer on hand can give you an excuse for not shaking hands, such as, \"I just sanitized, so I prefer not to shake.\"\n\n7. **Practice**: If you often find yourself in situations where handshakes are common, it might help to practice your preferred non-handshake greeting with friends or family to build your confidence.\n\nRemember that many people are becoming more aware of personal space and hygiene, so your choice may resonate with others as well.",
